document.title: Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Guide, Grade 6

534D800D393B4F67AA805838A44A5042.description:
Given only coordinates, calculate the distances between two points with the same first coordinate or the same
second coordinate using absolute value

A070B2901CCD4BBA911F14E1949DA257.description: Graph points in all four quadrants of the coordinate plane

6690067BF6F54041B1FFE2098C72EA00.description: Distinguish comparisons of absolute value from statements about order and apply to real world contexts

B52FF19F9386458396F619405FF1FF78.description: Interpret absolute value as magnitude for a positive or negative quantity in a real-world situation

diagram

7FEC51F56DD24B628AA1C64436F62BBA.description: Understand ordering and absolute value of rational numbers.

0E1A31101EBB454592D1C3BF610CA2B3.description: Order rational numbers on a number line

7B66D9143BB3461F8A094C0855479EC2.description:
Reason that when two ordered pairs differ only by signs, the locations of the points are related by reflections
across both axes

C21DE3EC65A64B53B3D3D8686A26A832.description: Find and position pairs of integers and other rational numbers on a coordinate plane

Recognize the signs of both numbers in an ordered pair; indicate which quadrant of the coordinate plane the
ordered pair will be located

B29D01EB7E964E48AB254908B0971510.description: Identify the location of 0 on a number line in relation to positive and negative numbers

0F09E28405EF4933A40DCA979934B109.description: Understand a rational number as a point on the number line. Extend number line diagrams and coordinate axes familiar from previous grades to represent points on the line and in the plane with negative number coordinates.

9270B572DCC541D98CBD8C753EA95EF3.description: Understand a rational number as a point on the number line. Extend number line diagrams and coordinate axes familiar from previous grades to represent points on the line and in the plane with negative number coordinates.

C538F41C74F84A21A659509ED7E48FFC.description: Explain where 0 fits into a situation represented by integers

68469539DF894A05A04A28A453CE21E3.description: Use integers to represent quantities in real world situations (above/below sea level, etc.)

7874615905D04FF0A9343E64AFB80B48.description: Identify an integer and its opposite

A98A9C9D01D0469BBC5AACD26D6777E4.description: Understand that positive and negative numbers are used together to describe quantities having opposite directions or values (e.g., temperature above/below zero, elevation above/below sea level, credits/debits, positive/negative electric charge); use positive and negative numbers to represent quantities in real-world contexts, explaining the meaning of 0 in each situation.

754FDEC91B954CD0B1EA24A8132D6FC7.description: Apply the Distributive Property to rewrite addition problems by factoring out the GCF

026BA2E3285A41ADBC462B7490D5737D.description:
Fluently identify the multiples of two whole numbers less than or equal to 12 and determine the Least Common
Multiple (LCM)

9C504D2419FE471193361394454950B5.description:
Fluently identify the factors of two whole numbers less than or equal to 100 and determine the Greatest
Common Factor (GCF)

1F40F0D55A4D4A3F982EAA4889654A31.description: Find the greatest common factor of two whole numbers less than or equal to 100 and the least common multiple of two whole numbers less than or equal to 12. Use the distributive property to express a sum of two whole numbers 1-100 with a common factor as a multiple of a sum of two whole numbers with no common factor. For example, express 36 + 8 as 4 (9 + 2).

D179A31EE165438B8AAE3521D665D8A4.description:
Fluently add, subtract, multiply, and divide multi-digit decimals using the standard algorithm for each operation
with speed and accuracy

9FCD49A3627C4B46B6D84BC489BEB040.description: Fluently divide multi-digit numbers using the standard algorithm with speed and accuracy

6AA66F06F85A4A3BAB162A6C5DE9C92A.description: Solve word problems involving division of fractions by fractions

A31714AACC2E4FBFB2883523D8E327C0.description: Compute quotients of fractions divided by fractions (including mixed numbers)

1BAA423803394065BF1DC12D5B2EE8E6.description: Interpret and compute quotients of fractions, and solve word problems involving division of fractions by fractions, e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem. For example, create a story context for (2/3) ÷ (3/4) and use a visual fraction model to show the quotient; use the relationship between multiplication and division to explain that (2/3) ÷ (3/4) = 8/9 because 3/4 of 8/9 is 2/3. (In general, (a/b) ÷ (c/d) = ad/bc.) How much chocolate will each person get if 3 people share 1/2 lb of chocolate equally? How many 3/4-cup servings are in 2/3 of a cup of yogurt? How wide is a rectangular strip of land with length 3/4 mi and area 1/2 square mi?.

E08B2E5C5BF74BA8ACFD669BE745803E.description:
Analyze the shape of the data distribution and the context in which the data were gathered to choose the
appropriate measures of central tendency and variability and justify why this measure is appropriate in terms of
content

A0A88AF3AF574D64BA6FF95810E280F0.description: Choose the appropriate measure of central tendency to represent data

70E03AE3731F4536BA65CDEC595B6B63.description: Determine the effect of outliers on quantitative measures of a set of data

126ACD2371834DC58095676F0E97FD8E.description: Report the number of observations in a data set or display

F8DA47F19D064944A3CF7C1035D1DE58.description: Organize and display data in tables and graphs

E94D003CBA4540C69C729A71D88641E4.description: Summarize numerical data sets in relation to their context, such as by: Reporting the number of observations; Describing the nature of the attribute under investigation, including how it was measured and its units of measurement; Giving quantitative measures of center (median and/or mean) and variability (interquartile range and/or mean absolute deviation), as well as describing any overall pattern and any striking deviations from the overall pattern with reference to the context in which the data were gathered; Relating the choice of measures of center and variability to the shape of the data distribution and the context in which the data were gathered.

A518FFF6A0674487888B35F65E09860B.description: Identify the components of dot plots, histograms, and box plots

1166CBAB321F4A958B1559483B14CCE0.description: Recognize that a measure of center for a numerical data set summarizes all of its values with a single number, while a measure of variation describes how its values vary with a single number.

31830F9A7E194EE9A3864524D6928033.description: Describe a set of data by its spread and overall shape

9CAC14E19ADD47F1B64E1B4B86273F53.description: Describe a set of data by its center

A928E1FD81C640479B317ABE301C010D.description: Know that a set of data has a distribution

14E3E8981C7C452FAF50A19021DD0277.description: Understand that a set of data collected to answer a statistical question has a distribution which can be described by its center, spread, and overall shape.

E534583EBAE8470897A115EB342992B8.description: Recognize a statistical question (examples versus non-examples)

62C4C19E95804CEF897D90D2360D9983.description: Recognize that data can have variability

6383D78B07324C878E1A938331AAABEF.description: Recognize a statistical question as one that anticipates variability in the data related to the question and accounts for it in the answers. For example, "How old am I?" is not a statistical question, but "How old are the students in my school?" is a statistical question because one anticipates variability in students' ages.

5B1F44CAFC664A6B8C4BE2B5E8AF987C.description: Solve real-world problems involving finding the whole, given a part and a percent

9FEAAB544DB24D9AAB110CB363F08171.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving ratio and rate

problems

4E1677C084C24DA8BC144B15CE85B0D9.description: Make a table of equivalent ratios using whole numbers

BA1B7F6841BF47399AF6B940ACAA92C6.description: Use ratio and rate reasoning to solve real-world and mathematical problems, e.g., by reasoning about tables of equivalent ratios, tape diagrams, double number line diagrams, or equations.

CCFEB0286DB54404BAC5A5F9E3CCFB65.description: Analyze the relationship between a ratio a:b and a unit rate a/b where b ≠ 0

1F6DF52EDA9946F9ACAAA1A657597875.description: Use appropriate math terminology as related to rate

7CA4C38951214D4B94751E866A7D6AF2.description: Identify and calculate a unit rate

BF8FB74AA33D4FCBBFD02AEC8EE4576B.description: Understand the concept of a unit rate a/b associated with a ratio a:b with b ≠ 0, and use rate language in the context of a ratio relationship. For example, "This recipe has a ratio of 3 cups of flour to 4 cups of sugar, so there is 3/4 cup of flour for each cup of sugar." "We paid $75 for 15 hamburgers, which is a rate of $5 per hamburger."

5F5A845EBFFB45E1B9FD65791AE225D1.description: Analyze your context to determine which type of ratio is represented

55B4AE87AB5147FD86BDA9C8DC2C3F03.description: Generalize that all ratios relate two quantities or measures within a given situation in a multiplicative relationship

29462A75B32D460689F35B4FF9BD80C1.description: Recognize that ratios appear in a variety of different contexts; part-to-whole, part-to-part, and rates

8870269758054627B5335D09DE8A8CCC.description: Know ratios compare two quantities; the quantities do not have to be the same unit of measure

67F41A2933B546A288E53EF1440AF57F.description: Know order matters when writing a ratio

4C0FD6B1DCAC47A3B1745A771CBF893F.description: Write ratio notation – a:b, a to b, a/b

E3C2602C389044289AD57D3D06BD2CF0.description: Understand the concept of a ratio and use ratio language to describe a ratio relationship between two quantities. For example, "The ratio of wings to beaks in the bird house at the zoo was 2:1, because for every 2 wings there was 1 beak." "For every vote candidate A received, candidate C received nearly three votes."

E6DC176A345C4FACA23ACCAD24161EFB.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving surface area using nets

5581597EE128487083459E13120145A8.description:
Apply knowledge of calculating the area of rectangles and triangles to a net, and combine the areas for each
shape into one answer representing the surface area of a three-dimensional figure

04D03818150D4550AA7775B9D216E57B.description:
Apply the technique of using coordinates to find the length of a side of a polygon drawn in the coordinate plane
to solve real-world and mathematical problems

EAA9A3BA018C45F0BB5F99823E100AD5.description: Use coordinates (with the same x-coordinate or the same y-coordinate) to find the length of a side of a polygon

Apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

406DC95E4E2F4BA384D6CEF0B244478C.description:

appropriate unit fraction edge lengths

Apply volume formulas for right rectangular prisms to solve real-world and mathematical problems involving
rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths

470AACD14EBF4EE6A5F44F53583E0967.description: Know how to calculate the volume of a right rectangular prism

Apply the formulas V = l w h and V = b h to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

2AE98377800143398F6A5415F3BBD660.description: Discuss, develop and justify formulas for triangles and parallelograms

CDA9698EE4944CDDB50A9C890DFB33D9.description:
Apply the techniques of composing and/or decomposing to find the area of triangles, special quadrilaterals and
polygons to solve mathematical real-world problems

DA09420C083549DB834770619CBEDA3B.description: Compare the area of a triangle to the area of the composed rectangle

2F8C53566A6648EB9B135BABCE443E07.description: Recognize and know how to compose and decompose polygons into triangles and rectangles

0471A2BA5B094D629BEED9139F9A857A.description: Find the area of right triangles, other triangles, special quadrilaterals, and polygons by composing into rectangles or decomposing into triangles and other shapes; apply these techniques in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

E6F56F9307AF4166A68991B1EC270321.description: Relate the data in a graph and table to the corresponding equation

49957390400248158CE39F979EBA4DDE.description: Analyze the relationship between the dependent variable and independent variable using tables and graphs

4B02BBE98EB24D56AAAE4262CD45F808.description: Write an equation to express one quantity (dependent) in terms of the other quantity (independent)

D59D63690A9148C1AD8AFB437FCE91EC.description: Use variables to represent two quantities in a real-world problem that change in relationship to one another

045E60BABCCB4208983F118698804B2A.description: Use variables to represent two quantities in a real-world problem that change in relationship to one another; write an equation to express one quantity, thought of as the dependent variable, in terms of the other quantity, thought of as the independent variable. Analyze the relationship between the dependent and independent variables using graphs and tables, and relate these to the equation. For example, in a problem involving motion at constant speed, list and graph ordered pairs of distances and times, and write the equation d = 65t to represent the relationship between distance and time.

4B86A63044714828B29BF3773D208F12.description:
Represent solutions to inequalities or the form x > c or x < c, with infinitely many solutions, on number line
diagrams

3708E06132E240BA9175911D3E8C8F48.description:
Write an inequality of the form x > c or x < c to represent a constraint or condition in a real-world or
mathematical problem

BFB7AC3564B7436A83E4C5B82F2FA6B1.description: Recognize that inequalities of the form x > c or x < c have infinitely many solutions

82686A706BEB49DB9CEBCE68CB2958C7.description: Identify the constraint or condition in a real-world or mathematical problem in order to set up an inequality

Recognize that inequalities of the form x > c or x < c have infinitely many solutions; represent solutions of such inequalities on number line diagrams.

975BEF715574462F847F113566882D74.description: Solve and write equations for real-world mathematical problems containing one unknown

Apply rules of the form x + p = q, and p x = q, for cases in which p, q and x are all nonnegative rational numbers, to
solve real-world and mathematical problems; with only one unknown quantity

775356E2503F4B3C83DD620AEC0EABC0.description: Solve real-world and mathematical problems by writing and solving equations of the form x + p = q and px = q for cases in which p, q and x are all nonnegative rational numbers.

E65FF715097243E19673703957979DA6.description: Write and evaluate numerical expressions involving whole-number exponents.
